properties.webBody:
This Watch & Act message is being issued for Bellbird Corner, Blore, Boisdale, Briagolong, Bulldog Junction, Bundalaguah, Bushy Park, Cobbannah, Coongulla, Culloden, Fernbank, Gillum, Glenaladale, Glenfalloch, Glenmaggie, Heyfield, Huggett, Hunter Corner, Iguana Creek, Koorool, Llowalong, Maffra, Maffra West Upper, Merrijig, Mewburn Park, Monomak, Moornapa, Morgan, Munro, Nap Nap Marra, Newry, Perry Bridge, Riverslea, Stockdale, Stratford, The Fingerboards, Tinamba, Tinamba West, Toolome, Valencia Creek, Walpa, Woodglen, Woolenook, Worrowing, Wrathung, Wrixon, Wuk Wuk.

  • The Licola-Mt Margaret Track fire, approximately 14 km north west of Valencia Creek, is not yet under control.
  • Spot fires are starting 6 km ahead of the main fire front.
  • This bushfire is moving quickly in south easterly direction towards Valencia Creek.
Don't wait, leaving now is the safest option - conditions may change and get worse very quickly.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing.
  • If you are away from home, do not return.

If the situation changes or you feel unsafe you should leave:
  • Take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area.

Emergency Services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.
Impacts in your area: 
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.
The next update is expected by 05/03/2019 06:50 pm or as the situation changes.

If you can smell smoke, please note:
  • Smoke can affect people's health.
  • People with heart or lung conditions (including asthma), children, pregnant women and older people are more sensitive to the effects of breathing in smoke.
  • People with existing heart or lung conditions (including asthma) should follow the treatment plan advised by the doctor.
Health information:
  • If you need medical advice for burns or exposure to smoke, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.
  • Anyone experiencing wheezing, chest tightness and difficulty breathing should call Triple Zero (000).
If you cannot smell smoke you are not likely to be exposed to smoke and it will therefore not affect you.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

  • There's a large bushfire in and around Bunyip State Park that is not yet under control.
  • Emergency services will continue to do fire suppression
  • Large aircraft will be working in the area
  • Smoke will be present in the area
There is currently no threat to you, but you should stay informed and monitor conditions as these fires are very unpredictable.
What you should do: 
  • Monitor warnings so you can act quickly if the situation changes.
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing.
  • If you have time, check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions.
  • Keep the roads clear so emergency services can respond.
  • Review your fire survival plan.


Road Closures:

  • The Princes Freeway has Re-Opened 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
  • Road closures remain in place including the following Princes Freeway off ramps:                           
  •      Brew Road, Garfield North Road, Tonimbuk Road & Bessie Creek road
  • For residents only Maryknoll area access can be made at  the intersection of Bessie Creek and Moore Road, Victoria Police are positioned at this intersection and will issue Residents with a  wrist band on photo and residential address identification. (some roads in Maryknoll area remain closed)
  • Wrist bands are available from Victoria Police located at Nar Nar Goon recreation reserve, Spencer Street, Nar Nar Goon.  Photo and residential address identification required to obtain wrist bands 

Have you relocated or displaced?  
If you have relocated or have been displaced, please register via the Red Cross website register "Find Reunite” (Link opens in another window) and include any concerns or issues around your livestock or alternatively register at a relief centre

Other:
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads
  • Emergency services will remain in the area
  • Aircraft may be flying overhead
  • Smoke will be visible from nearby communities and roads as far as Thorpdale.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.


For more information on preparing for bushfires visit: www.cfa.vic.gov.au/plan-prepare.

  • 4:00 pm Drouin Cricket Club, Bellbird Park 271 Settlement road, 
  • 6:00 pm Cardinia Cultural Center, 40 Lakeside Boulevard, Pakenham


Relief Centres:
  • Pakenham Hall located at the corner of John and Henry Street, Pakenham
  • Bellbird Park Indoor Centre located at 270 Settlement Road, Drouin 
Recovery Centre:
  • A recovery centre will be open at the Bunyip Showgrounds and Recreation Centre located at Longwarry - Nar Nar Goon Road, Bunyip to answer any questions you may have on :    
    • Tues-Fri this week 10am to 6:30pm  (5th, 6th, 7th, 8th Mar)
    • Sat, Sun and Mon 10am to 4pm       (9th, 10th,11th Mar)
    • Tue-Fri next week 10am to 6:30pm  (12th, 13th, 14th, 15th Mar)
    Contacts
    • Cardinia Shire Council 1300 787 624
    • Baw Baw Shire 1300 229 229

Livestock Management:
  • The equestrian section of Akoonah Park, Berwick is available for people to take horses in floats.  To access this facility, turn off Princes Highway into Manuka Road, then into Funston Street.  Enter Akoonah Park via Gate 7. Water and toilet facilities are available.  Horses must be contained and not left unattended.  The owners are responsible for their horses at all times. 

Managing animals when their are fires:
  • Move your animals to a designated low risk area early in the day
  • Don't shut horses in stables or small yards, unless the area is well protected from bushfire - horses instinctively run through or around flames to previously burnt ground
  • Do not let livestock, or horses onto roads, as they cause a huge risk to public safety and themselves, particularly in smoky conditions
  • Remove equipment that may burn animals during bushfire such as rugs, nylon, plastic halters or collars and fly veils.
  • Fill water troughs and put out sufficient feed for 4-5 days

Evacuating pets and other animals:
  • On high risk days don't let your pets out unsupervised, as they may take fright and run away.
  • Confine them early.  Pets are safest inside a secure room, on a lead or in carriers
  • Allow enough time to act - stay aware of possible emergencies on your evacuation route.
  • Call ahead to your planned evacuation location, or your local council to check which centres are open for animals.
  • Grab the emergency evacuation kit; ensure you include your pets medications and vaccination certificates
  • Do not leave pets unattended in vehicles

  • The Watch and Act message for Dinner Plain has been downgraded.  There is no imminent danger to the community of Dinner Plain. 
  • There is a bushfire centred 8Km South West of Dinner Plain at Mayford Tuckalong Spur that is not yet under control.
  • This fire has grown to 3500Ha and is continuing to burn to the east of the Dargo High Plains road and has crossed the Dargo River to the west in two isolated areas.  
  • The fire is travelling in a south easterly direction.
  • Several new fires have been started by lightning strikes in the area south of Cobungra.
  • Ground crews and aircraft are actively fighting this fire

There is currently no threat to you, but you should consider your options for preparing your property or prepare to leave early.

Continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.

For information on water goto: https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/bushfires-and-water-tanks   

The most effective way to prevent contamination of your water tank is to make sure it is properly sealed and to disconnect the downpipes to the tank. Do not reconnect the downpipes until the roof has been cleaned after the bushfire, either manually or after a flush of rain.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water quality at Mullinger Swamp.

  • High levels of Blue Green Algae have been detected in the Mullinger Swamp. 
  • The algal bloom is expected to remain until there is significant rainfall to flush the swamp or cooler conditions slow the algae.
  • Regular testing is being conducted to identify new outbreaks or changes that might indicate improved water quality.
  • This notification will be reviewed weekly and updated as the situation changes.
Warning signs have been installed at the Mullinger Swamp.

You should avoid direct contact with affected water in the swamp.

Do not swim in affected areas or use water for cooking, drinking, washing or showering. Boiling the water will not make it safe. 
What you should do:
  • Visit the Parks Victoria Website for more information. 
  • Observe information signs posted at the Mullinger Swamp.
Protect your health:
  • Direct contact with water affected by blue green algae can cause skin irritation, sore eyes, ears and nose. If swallowed it can cause cramps, nausea and vomiting. 
  • If you do come into contact with affected water, wash your skin immediately in clean cool water. 
  • Boiling affected water does not make it safe to drink. Boiling water bursts the blue green algae cells and releases toxins into the water making it more likely that you will experience symptoms. 
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.

Protect your pets:
  • Pet owners should prevent pets from drinking or having direct contact with contaminated water. 
Agriculture information:
Irrigation water contaminated with blue green algae should not be spray irrigated on vegetables and fruit, or come in contact with plants being grown for food during processing and packing. - Fruit and vegetables grown in the affected areas are safe to consume if farmers follow recommendations regarding blue green algae.

Visitors to the area are advised that they can still enjoy other recreational activities such as bushwalking and sightseeing. 

Impacts in your area:
  • The water is  green as a result of the algae bloom.

Boating and fishing:
  • Boating and fishing is still allowed in these areas, however care needs to be taken.
  • Fish caught from affected areas should be rinsed and cleaned thoroughly in fresh water, and internal organs removed from the fish and discarded before eating. 
  • Do not eat mussels, crayfish or yabbies caught from the affected area. 
If you see fish that are dead, dying or swimming erratically do not touch or eat them.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 08/03/2019 10:30 am or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.
  • For information on blue green algae and stock visit: http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/agriculture/pests-diseases-and-weeds/animal-diseases/beef-and-dairy-cows/blue-green-algal -poisoning-of-stock.
  • FOr information on blue green algae and irrigation visit: http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/agriculture/farm-management/soil-and-water/irrigation/blue-green-algae-and-irrigation-water.

  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter.
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This message is being issued for water quality at Lake Charlegrark.

  • High levels of Blue Green Algae have been detected in Lake Charlegrark since mid-January.
  • The algal bloom is expected to remain until there is significant rainfall to flush the lake or cooler conditions slow the algae.
  • Regular testing is being conducted to identify changes that might indicate improved water quality.
  • This notification will be reviewed weekly and updated as situation changes.
Warning signs have been installed at the lake.

You should avoid direct contact with affected water in Lake Charlegrark. 

Do not swim in affected areas or use water for cooking, drinking, washing or showering. Boiling the water will not make it safe. 


 
What you should do
  • Visit the Parks Victoria Website for more information. 
  • Observe information signs posted at the lake.

Protect your health:
  • Direct contact with water affected by blue green algae can cause skin irritation, sore eyes, ears and nose. If swallowed it can cause cramps, nausea and vomiting. 
  • If you do come into contact with affected water, wash your skin immediately in clean cool water. 
  • Boiling affected water does not make it safe to drink. Boiling water bursts the blue green algae cells and releases toxins into the water making it more likely that you will experience symptoms. 
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.

Protect your pets:
  • Pet owners should prevent pets from drinking or having direct contact with contaminated water. 
Visitors to the area are advised that they can still enjoy other recreational activities such as bushwalking and sightseeing. 

Impacts in your area:
  • The water is green as a result of the algae bloom.
Boating and fishing:
  • Boating and fishing is still allowed in these areas, however care needs to be taken.
  • Fish caught from affected areas should be rinsed and cleaned thoroughly in fresh water, and internal organs removed from the fish and discarded before eating. 
  • Do not eat mussels, crayfish or yabbies caught from the affected area. 
If you see fish that are dead, dying or swimming erratically do not touch or eat them.
This message was issued by Department of Environment Land Water and Planning.

The next update is expected by 08/03/2019 10:30 am or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.
  • For information on blue green algae and stock visit: http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/agriculture/pests-diseases-and-weeds/animal-diseases/beef-and-dairy-cows/blue-green-algal -poisoning-of-stock.
  • FOr information on blue green algae and irrigation visit: http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/agriculture/farm-management/soil-and-water/irrigation/blue-green-algae-and-irrigation-water.

  • VicEmergency app.

This Watch & Act message is being issued for Cambarville, East Warburton, McMahons Creek, Reefton, Upper Yarra Dam, Warburton.

  • There is a bushfire in the Upper Yarra Catchment that is not yet under control.
  • The bushfire is travelling in a south-easterly direction towards Reefton. 
  • The fire has crossed containment lines and firefighters have been unable to stop the spread of the fire. 
  • This bushfire could impact Reefton by 7.00 pm tonight. 
  • Your safest option is to leave now and travel towards Warburton.
  • Spot fires are occurring around the Upper Yarra Reservoir. The Reservoir is now closed. You need to leave immediately if you are in the Reservoir Park
  • For information on the fires a Community Meeting will be held tonight at 7pm. Warburton Fire Station 3484 Warburton Highway. Warburton. Mel. 290B4
Don't wait, leaving now is the safest option - conditions may change and get worse very quickly.


What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing.
  • If you are away from home, do not return.
  • If you have time, check your neighbours to see if they are monitoring conditions.
  • Review your fire survival plan.

If the situation changes or you feel unsafe you should leave:
  • Take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area.  

Emergency Services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.
Impacts in your area: 
  • The following roads are closed: Warburton-Woods Point Road between Stream Road Reefton and Cumberland Junction.
  • There is no access to Marysville or Woods Point via the Warburton-Woods Point Road.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message replaces the Advice message issued yesterday for Bald Hills, Buchan, Buchan South, Butchers Ridge, Gelantipy, Gillingall, Murrindal, Sunny Point, Timbarra, W Tree, Wulgulmerang West.

  • The bushfire north of Timbarra and Buchan and west of the Gelantipy Road between Gelantipy and Murrindal is contained.  
  • Work is continuing on this fire including burning out and strengthening containment lines, identifying and treating hot spots, patrolling and blacking out along the fire edge.
  • Crews and large machinery are on the ground rehabilitating forest roads and control lines within the burnt area and managing hazardous trees. 
  • Warm and dry conditions along with lightning are expected today which could increase fire activity or start new ones.
  • Smoke remains visible in the area but the fire is well within containment lines.
  • EPA air monitoring will stay in place until it is no longer required.
  • Lightning has started several new fires in the area, ground crews and aircraft are working on the fires
There is currently no threat to you, but you should plan for what you will do if the situation changes.


What you should do: 

  • It is important not to become too relaxed with the fires being officially called 'contained'.     
  • Please remain aware of local conditions and your own situation, including where to get information, as conditions become hotter and drier.
  • Stay safe when travelling.  Be aware of slow-moving, heavy machinery that may be using local roads.
  • Review your fire survival plan.
  • If you do not have a plan, decide what you will do if the situation changes. Go to: http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/plan-prepare/before-and-during-a-fire/
  •   The most effective way to prevent contamination of your water tank is to make sure it is properly sealed and to disconnect the downpipes to the tank. Do not reconnect the downpipes until the roof has been cleaned after the bushfire, either manually or after a flush of rain.
  • https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/bushfires-and-water-tanks
Impacts in your area: 

  • Gelantipy Road is open.
  • Emergency Services will remain in the area for as long as necessary to completely extinguish the fire. 
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby communities and roads.
  • Trees can be extremely hazardous during a bushfire.  Fire affected or burnt trees can fall on you without warning.  Avoid standing, parking or travelling through fire affected areas. 
  • For recovery information contact East Gippsland Shire Council on the Recovery Hotline 1800 100 298 and the VicEmergency Website. 
Road Closures:

  • Timbarra Road is open to local traffic and emergency vehicles only.
  • Glenmore Road is closed.
  • Timbarra Camp Ground remains closed.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/) or call 13 11 70 for road closures.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 06/03/2019 01:30 pm or as the situation changes.

  • People with heart or lung conditions (including asthma), children, pregnant women and older people are more sensitive to the effects of breathing in smoke.

Wildlife

  • Please report any sick or injured wildlife directly to DELWP on 136 186 we can then allocate an appropriate person to deal with the matter
  •  Please don’t approach or give water to injured animals you might think you are helping but the animal is likely in shock and you may do more harm than good so leave it to the experts. 
  • Wildlife require skilled care, treatment and rehabilitation to recover sufficiently to be returned to the wild. Without this skilled care, wildlife may not recover or may lose their natural behaviours.
  • It is illegal in Victoria to keep sick, injured or orphaned wildlife as a pet.

properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for Boisdale, Coongulla, Glenmaggie, Glenmaggie Point, Koorool, Maffra West Upper, Monomak, Newry, Valencia Creek.

  • The Licola-Mt Margaret Track Fire, approximately 4km north west of Valencia Creek, is not yet under control.
  • Spot fires are starting 6km ahead of the main fire front.
  • This bushfire is moving quickly in a south easterly direction towards Valencia Creek
Valencia Creek  and surrounding area could be impacted anytime.
Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. 
Emergency Services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.
What you should do: 

Travel to: 
  • People  leaving the area can now go to the emergency relief centre located at the Baptist Church, Cobains Rd, Sale.
  •   You should leave using roads leading south away from the warning area.
  • The home of family or friends that is away from the warning area.
  • When you leave remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications.

In the car: 
  • If you are travelling, do not enter the area. U-turn to safety.
  • Slow down and turn on your headlights. Smoke will make it difficult to see.

If you are unable to leave you should shelter indoors:
  • Close all exterior doors, windows and vents. Turn off cooling systems.
  • You must take shelter before the fire arrives. The extreme heat is likely to kill you well before the flames reach you.
  • Shelter in a room that has two exits including one directly to the outside. It is important to be able to see outside so you know what is happening with the fire.
  • If your home catches on fire and the conditions inside become unbearable, you need to get out and go to an area that has already been burnt. 

If you cannot get indoors, other last resort options include:
  • Shelter in the middle of a large open area like a ploughed paddock, football oval or sporting reserve.
  • Get into a large body of water like a dam, lake, river, the ocean or inground pool.
  • Try to protect yourself from the fire's heat.

If you are caught in fire in your car:
  • Park behind a solid structure to block the fire's heat or pull over to cleared area.
  • Try to position the car towards the approaching fire.
  • Turn on your hazard lights and headlights.
  • Close all windows.
  • Turn off the air-coniditiong and shut all the air vents.
  • Turn your car engine off.
  • Get down as low as possible below window level and cover up with a woollen blanket.
Impacts in your area: 

This bushfire is starting spot fires and embers are being carried by the wind ahead of the main fire. 

This messages was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 05/03/2019 07:10 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water quality at Lake Bolac.

  • High levels of Blue Green Algae have been detected in the lake. 
  • The algal bloom is expected to remain until there is significant rainfall to flush the lake or cooler conditions slow the algae.
  • Regular testing is being conducted to identify new outbreaks or changes that might indicate improved water quality.
  • This notification will be reviewed weekly and updated as the situation changes.
Warning signs have been installed at the lake.

You should avoid direct contact with affected water in Lake Bolac.

Do not swim in affected areas or use water for cooking, drinking, washing or showering. Boiling the water will not make it safe. 

What you should do:
  • Visit the Parks Victoria Website for more information. 
  • Observe information signs posted at the lake. 

Protect your health:
  • Direct contact with water affected by blue green algae can cause skin irritation, sore eyes, ears and nose. If swallowed it can cause cramps, nausea and vomiting. 
  • If you do come into contact with affected water, wash your skin immediately in clean cool water. 
  • Boiling affected water does not make it safe to drink. Boiling water bursts the blue green algae cells and releases toxins into the water making it more likely that you will experience symptoms. 
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctor or Nurse-On-Call on 1300 60 60 24.

Protect your pets:
  • Pet owners should prevent pets from drinking or having direct contact with contaminated water. 

Agriculture information: 
Irrigation water contaminated with blue green algae should not be spray irrigated on vegetables and fruit, or come in contact with plants being grown for food during processing and packing. - Fruit and vegetables grown in the affected areas are safe to consume if farmers follow recommendations regarding blue green algae.
Visitors to the area are advised that they can still enjoy other recreational activities such as bushwalking and sightseeing.  

Impacts in your area:
  • The water is green as a result of the algae bloom.

Boating and fishing:
  • Boating and fishing is still allowed in these areas, however care needs to be taken.
  • Fish caught from affected areas should be rinsed and cleaned thoroughly in fresh water, and internal organs removed from the fish and discarded before eating. 
  • Do not eat mussels, crayfish or yabbies caught from the affected area. 
If you see fish that are dead, dying or swimming erratically do not touch or eat them.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 08/03/2019 10:30 am or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.
  • For information on blue green algae and stock visit: http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/agriculture/pests-diseases-and-weeds/animal-diseases/beef-and-dairy-cows/blue-green-algal -poisoning-of-stock.
  • FOr information on blue green algae and irrigation visit: http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/agriculture/farm-management/soil-and-water/irrigation/blue-green-algae-and-irrigation-water.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Budgeree East, Jeeralang Junction, Jumbuk, Yinnar South
properties.webBody:
This Watch & Act message is being issued for Budgeree East, Jeeralang Junction, Jumbuk, Yinnar South and Jumbuck Road in the vicinity of the Morwell National Park.

  • There is a bushfire at 1.8 km south of Yinnar South not yet under control. 
  •  The bushfire has increased to 1820 hectares. 
  •  The fire has not grown significantly in size, with some fire activity on the northern edge within the Morwell National Park, on the eastern edge near Jumbuk Road south of Summerfields Road and on the south western edge near Whitelaws Track. 
  •  Crews are working on these edges as well as focusing on asset protection. 
  •  Aircraft will be visible and are assisting crews in the area. 
  • Power line and tree hazard/s assessment and treatment is occurring.   
  •  There will be power outages in the vicinity of the fire whilst the location is made safe.
Don't wait, leaving now is the safest option - conditions may change and get worse very quickly.

Communities should monitor conditions and information and share with family and friends for greater awareness
What you should do: 
  • Monitor changes to the situation. Increased wind speed, change in wind direction, smoke or poor visibility can indicate the situation is changing.
  • If you are away from home, do not return.

If the situation changes or you feel unsafe you should leave:
  • A relief centre is open at Kernot Hall in Morwell, 50-70 Princes Drive, Morwell, 1300 367 700
  • Take your pets, medications, mobile phone and charger.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends that are away from the warning area.

Emergency Services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Check emergency school closures in your area at www.education.vic.gov.au
  • Multiple roads have been closed, please check www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au 
  • All road closed signs are to be respected for your safety and firefighter safety 
  • Trees can fall unexpectedly across roads and cause dangerous driving conditions.
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.
The next update is expected by 06/03/2019 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

Smoke can affect people's health. 
  • If you are sensitive to smoke you should avoid prolonged or heavy physical activity. Where possible you should try to stay indoors.
  • People with heart or lung conditions (including asthma), children, pregnant women and older people are more sensitive to the effects of breathing in smoke.
  • People with existing heart or lung conditions (including asthma) should follow the treatment plan advised by the doctor.
Health information:
  • If you need medical advice for burns or exposure to smoke, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.
  • Anyone experiencing wheezing, chest tightness and difficulty breathing should call Triple Zero (000).
If you cannot smell smoke you are not likely to be exposed to smoke and it will therefore not affect you.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webHeadline:

Severe thunderstorms are no longer occurring in the Northern Country and North Central districts and the warning for these districts is CANCELLED.
